 Indoš
09.06.2018 15:01:09
The word 'medicine' to North American Indians has many meanings. It doesn't
just mean 'something sacred', as everything has a measure of sanctity, but
refers more the influence that something or someone has (over nature,
themselves, other beings). Someone who is moved in spirit to make cooking pots
very well may be referred to as having good medicine in that area. Being pious
or devout and sincere about it might make people say of you that you practice
good medicine in your prayers. Conversly someone whose intent is to harm or
influence others for the benefit of only themselves is said to be practicing
bad medicine- or even to 'have' bad medicine if it's in their nature to be
'bad'. A place can have good medicine if you go there and good things happen
to you or you feel good there.

All things to the NA Indians are sacred and have medicine - some medicine is
much stronger (has more influence) than others. But it depends on the tribe,
what they believe, what works for the people involved, and what the medicine
is being used for that makes it 'big' or 'strong'."

Tolik nějaký sečtělý amík z anonymní diskuse.
Čili, pokud to nemělo být vlastní jméno pro indiánskou squaw nebo zvířátko -
